post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8314739_8314757_0": {"length": 45, "quality": 0.8181818181818182, "section_id": 7182}}, "n3337": {"so_8314739_8314757_0": {"length": 45, "quality": 0.8181818181818182, "section_id": 6926}}}, "8314950": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>delete[] destroys (or destructs) a number of objects and then frees the memory. If the type is not an object, it simply frees the memory without calling destructors. This would be good:</p>\n<pre><code> class some_class\n {\n       some_class(int);\n };\n\n ....\n some_class *p = new some_class[[2]](0)(1);\n\n delete[] p; // delete calculates how many objects where created, and call destructors of all objects, then frees the memory (which is twice sizeof(some_class)\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-29T17:20:44.937", "Id": "8314950", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-11-29T17:20:44.937", "ParentId": "8314739", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "837803"}, "8314769": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It is not necessary and would have no effect. You are casting a <code>char*</code> to a <code>char*</code>.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-29T17:08:17.810", "Id": "8314769", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-11-29T17:08:17.810", "ParentId": "8314739", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1033896"}, "8314739": {"ViewCount": "249", "Body": "<p>Which of these should be used?</p>\n<pre><code>char *ex = new char[255];\n// code\ndelete [] ex;\n</code></pre>\n<p>or</p>\n<pre><code>char *ex = new char[255];\n// code\ndelete [] (char *) ex;\n</code></pre>\n<p>I'm thinking that the cast isn't necessary, but would it have any effect on the actual deletion?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8314757", "Title": "deleting a char array with cast to char*?", "CreationDate": "2011-11-29T17:06:04.317", "Id": "8314739", "CommentCount": "1", "LastEditDate": "2011-11-29T17:06:58.977", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "298661", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-29T17:20:44.937", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "1071777", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "8314757": {"Id": "8314757", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<pre><code>char *ex = new char[255];\n// code\ndelete [] ex;\n</code></pre>\n<p>You do not need to cast, The cast won't have any effect anyways.    </p>\n<p>The C++ Standard does not need you to do any casting. Here is the reference.</p>\n<p><strong>Section \u00a73.7.3.2.3:</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8314739_8314757_0\">The value of the first argument supplied to one of the deallocation functions provided in the standard library may be a null pointer value; if so, the call to the deallocation function has no effect. <strong>Otherwise, the value supplied to <code>operator delete(void*)</code> in the standard library shall be one of the values returned by a previous invocation of either <code>operator new(size_t)</code> or <code>operator new(size_t, const std::nothrow_t&amp;)</code> in the standard library, and the value supplied to operator <code>delete[](void*)</code> in the standard library shall be one of the values returned by a previous invocation of either <code>operator new[](size_t)</code> or <code>operator new[](size_t, const std::nothrow_t&amp;)</code> in the standard library.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "452307", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-29T17:14:24.110", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-11-29T17:07:28.093", "ParentId": "8314739", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "452307", "LastEditDate": "2011-11-29T17:14:24.110"}});